Protagoras of Abdera c. 490 – 420 BCE
Region / Tradition: Thrace / Athens (Greek)
School / Movement: The Sophists (The First and Greatest)

Core Domains
Epistemology: Relativism (Subjectivism); Perspectivism.

Ethics: Social Contract; Civic Virtue (Arete).

Political: Democracy; The art of Rhetoric and debate.

Language: Orthoepeia (The correct use of words); Grammar.

Religion: Agnosticism.

Central Questions
What problem(s) were they trying to solve: How to succeed in the newly democratic Athens where power depended on the ability to persuade others in public assembly.

What tension or paradox defines their work: The tension between Physis (nature) and Nomos (human law/custom)—are values natural or merely agreed-upon inventions?

What question do they inherit: The Pre-Socratic search for a single truth, which Protagoras rejected as impossible or useless.

What question do they bequeath: "Is there such a thing as objective truth, or is truth just whatever the majority agrees on?"

Key Ideas
Concept 1: Man is the Measure: The famous "Homo Mensura" dictum: "Man is the measure of all things; of things that are, that they are, and of things that are not, that they are not."

Concept 2: Two Sides to Every Issue: The claim that for every argument, there is an equally valid counter-argument (Dissoi Logoi).

Concept 3: Making the Weaker Argument the Stronger: The practice of teaching students how to win a debate regardless of the "truth" of the position, focusing on the utility of persuasion.

Concept 4: Agnosticism regarding the Gods: He famously stated that concerning the gods, he had no way of knowing whether they exist or what they are like, due to the shortness of human life and the obscurity of the subject.

Method / Style
Rhetorical and Pragmatic.
Protagoras was a professional teacher (a "Sophist") who charged high fees. He defined truth not as a mirror of nature, but as a "useful belief" that helps an individual or a city-state function effectively.

Influences
Heraclitus: Adopted the idea of constant flux—if everything is always changing, then "truth" can only be a temporary perception of an individual.

The Rise of Athenian Democracy: The historical shift from aristocratic rule to public debate created the market for his skills.

Impact
Immediate reception: Extremely famous and wealthy, but also controversial; his books were reportedly burned in Athens due to his agnosticism.

Long-term influence: Forced Socrates and Plato to spend their lives trying to prove that objective truth does exist against the "threat" of relativism.

Modern relevance: The direct ancestor of Pragmatism, Postmodernism, and the study of Rhetoric and Communication Theory.

Critiques
Famous objections: Plato's "Self-Refutation" argument: If Protagoras says "all truth is relative," then that statement itself must be relative and not objectively true for everyone.

Internal contradictions: He claimed to teach "virtue," but if truth is relative, whose version of virtue was he teaching?

Archetypal Summary
Protagoras as the lawyer of the mind, who moved the focus of philosophy from the stars and elements to the human experience and the power of the word.

